{You are South and it is your bid. Decide what you would say, then  on BID. 

There is an excellent bidding guideline which tells you how to respond with two 4-card Majors. You bid them "up-the-line". That means you bid 1\H.

Partner's rebid is 1\S. What do you bid? 

This hand shows why responder should bid "up-the-line". Partner can now show a 4-card \S suit at the 1-level. Imagine the suits reversed - you first respond with 1\S. If partner wanted to show a \H suit he would have to go to the 2-level, and he might not have the strength to do so.

Back to the actual situation. Over partner's 1\S bid you jump to 3\S. This jump shows about 11-12 points and good \S support (4 cards). In case you thought this showed 13 or more points that wouldn't be logical. If you had 13 points and 4 \Ss you would jump all the way to game. So 3\S is invitational. Partner accepts the invitation.

North would play 4\S.

South plays 4\S. West leads the \D2. East plays \DJ.

Losers: \S 1 : \H 0 : \D 2 : \C 2 : Total = 5

Counting losers from the South hand you have 2 \C losers to get rid of. If you had counted from the North hand there would have been 2 \H losers to get rid of. In any case the plan is the same.

Win the \DA and play \SA and \SK. If the \Ss split 3-2 you are home-free. Leave the master trump out and play your \C A K and dummy's \H A K. Then cross-ruff \Cs and \Hs. Whichever defender holds the last trump is welcome to ruff with it at any time. The defense is also welcome to take their 2 \Ds at any time. Your T tricks are safe.

North and South were able to make all their small trumps individually.

If East ruffs the fourth \H with his master \SQ South just discards a \D loser and makes an overtrick.}
